good UI and interactive but sounds became difficult to monitor
I kept getting the radiation and temperature sounds mixed up and some sounds overlapped and it was difficult to know which is which, especially when a robot was setting off an alarm

During the introduction I didn't make a conscious effort to pair the sounds to their meanings. When I began the experiment I was unable to identify which sound corresponded to what. By the end of the experiment I could feel that I was able to naturally distinguish the different sounds and intensities, but still did not know their meanings.
A mini map would be useful. Also being able to have the robot continue waypoint driving after deselecting them would be useful for exploration

i was overwhelmed by the sounds coming from each robot - it would be nice to disable them whilst the left hand listening mode is engaged to allow me to focus on the tagging of an area. I also felt that the robots should only ask for assistance if they have developed a serious fault, because it was hard to think about saving the robots as well as tagging. Essentially, if it was easy to switch functionality on/off to help the user focus I think it would be less overwhelming :)

The Radiation and the Temperature sounds were too similar at the higher levels when they were played at the same time. It was easier to identify the Gas when all the sounds were played, the Radiation and the Temperature sounds might need a little more of a difference like the Gas.

Initially the user felt to rushed, then when i was accostomed to a worflow to look for sybols first then investigate the area then the i consumed time more efficiently during the investigation. When radiation and temperature mix up it kind of hard to distinguish
I ended up focusing on just the real time listening mode as I found trying to multitask to do other things to distracting, so ignored the safety alarms for robots etc
I could not remember which was temperature and radiation sounds

The alerts were very distracting, they made it difficult to process what you were hearing while carrying out real-time listening. The Radiaton and Temperature alarms were good as they were constant, the Gas alarm was easily identifiable but because it wasn't constant it was difficult to tell whether you were in an area of gas or whether you were hearing an alert.

1. I need a map to navigate and know the place and the location of robots 2. I need an indicator to know which robot is sensing the hazards. 3. I need a transport system that could direct me to the robot without me finding the robot in the middle of nowhere
Differentiating the cymbal gas sounds from low to high got quite tricky whereas it was clear in the other sound options
It was slightly difficult to determine between low and medium levels for the radiation and the temperature alarms
I liked the distinctness of each sound and that they were associated with the hazards, but I did find the radiation sound slightly painful to listen to
There were too many robots and clumsy audio which did not allow me to concentrate on what I was required to do.
I resorted more to real time audio than the alerts, just checked the alerts when I had time
after time I became familiar with the sounds and found identification much easier. Some of the auxiliary sounds the robots made where distracting
leaving and re-entering a hazardous area sometimes caused a delay in the sound being triggered
Difficult to discern real-time listening sounds from the sounds the robot was hearing, making it a bit confusing at times
I found it hard to interact with the robots themselves (Taking them out of harms way)
It could be added a mini map to identify the position of each robot.
It's hard to determine the sound source. Hard to control the robots as they take longer paths. Slow robots. Hard to multitask robots/myself.
a lot of sound all at once can be a bit disorientating to tell where the actual source is coming from.
would be better if there was no robot noise at all. Just leaving the tags behind and determining the sounds from the tags.
Overall, it was a fantastic experience. The instructions are clear to follow as it was my first VR experience.

Despite my answers, the sounds for radiation and gas are somewhat instinctive for what they represent, however I note that in practicality I almost naturally discarded hearing the gas sound when combined with other sounds. I also note that the robot's various sounds where distracting while trying to tag items using local listening. It would also be useful to be able to track the robots location through walls or in the discovered area as I was in a room without them frequently and didn't know where they where while they alarmed.
3d Binaural audio needs improving - difficult to gauge direction sound comes from

the sounds of temperature and radiation hazard were somewhat confusing, although gas one was clear. i think the low-high frequency of the sounds should be different and more of an associsiation with the radiation - like "silent hill" alarm and temperature should be smt else. It is bit confusing because of when the hazard is high, the volume increases therefore making temperature-low sound increases in pitch therefore making it hard to distinguish from radiation hazard. the rest was really good experience and entertaining, despite the importance of the task.
4 robots was too many. Felt like worrying after my own children running around
Maybe using a 3D heatmap to show the hazard would be more intuitive.
